<|startoftext|>Question:A person with severe depression is asked to come to the emergency room at a hospital. Is there a medicare program that can help
Answer:Well, I think it would be best if this person's situation was treated as a serious illness and their meds and meds were taken.  Just remember - you can't make everything right.  As for the people who are asking for emergency room space, most hospitals are not too eager to accommodate this kind of person.  If you are seriously suffering with any health or depression, call your health or mental health services (they generally are in crisis and require a referral to a specialist) and ask what is needed in this situation.  Meds such as meds, antidepressant medications, etc. are often used in crisis situations.  There will be a shortage of meds, meds you need, and resources to take care of these type of issues for your meds.  You might also ask your health or mental health services to give you a referral to an specialist who specializes in depression and anxiety and other disorders.  Even if you go to that specialist, you can still ask for a free (non-emergency) meds at the appropriate hospital.  You have the opportunity to meet at the emergency room with a specialist and ask questions and ask to be provided with a referral, but it would be best to talk to the person at the hospital or your health or mental health services.  Good luck! =)<|endoftext|>
